  <static seed="114" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FractionArithmetic/AddingFractionsOfInches10.pg">
    <statement><p>A <m>2\times4</m> piece of lumber in your garage is <m>{41{\textstyle\frac{7}{16}}}</m> inches long. A second <m>2\times4</m> is <m>{54{\textstyle\frac{5}{8}}}</m> inches long. If you lay them end to end, what will the total length be?</p>
<p>The total length will be <fillin characters="7" name="AnSwEr0001"/> inches.</p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>96{\textstyle\frac{1}{16}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To find the total length in inches, we add the two lengths together.</p>
<p><m>\begin{aligned}
    {41{\textstyle\frac{7}{16}}}+{54{\textstyle\frac{5}{8}}} \amp  = 41+\frac{7}{16}+54+\frac{5}{8}\\
                \amp  = 95+\frac{7}{16}+\frac{5}{8}\\
                \amp  = 95+{1{\textstyle\frac{1}{16}}}\\
                \amp  = {96{\textstyle\frac{1}{16}}}
\end{aligned}</m></p>
<p>So the total length is <m>{96{\textstyle\frac{1}{16}}}</m> inches.</p>
</solution>
